{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505005"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:24:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:24:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2396"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2396"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.63,0.08,0.14,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2396"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82732"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2396"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2396"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67867"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2078"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1640"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1682"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9813"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43140"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82732"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of shortness of breath and new-onset left-sided chest pain first noticed when he awoke that morning. He describes the chest pain as sharp and worsens with inspiration. He has a known history of panic disorder, and hypertension, for which he takes perindopril 4mg and fluoxetine 20 mg once a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo days ago, he flew home to Adelaide from a conference in Berlin as part of his job. He does not smoke but enjoys a glass of wine with most dinners. Temperature is 37.2 C, blood pressure is 100/65 mmHg, pulse is 114/min and regular, and respirations are 24/min. The physical examination is unremarkable except for mild tenderness and swelling in his left leg. His laboratory results are shown below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETroponin I= 0.05 ng/ml\u003C/strong\u003E (Reference range: 0\u20130.04 ng/ml)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"An ECG is performed. In addition to sinus tachycardia, which one of the following ECG changes is most likely present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["S-T segment elevation in the lateral leads","T-wave inversion in the right precordial leads","New onset left bundle branch block","ST-segment elevation in all the precordial leads","Prolonged QT- interval"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with a history of sudden onset pleuritic chest pain (i.e., a chest pain that worsens with inspiration), dyspnoea, and recent history of immobilisation due to air travel with leg swelling is suspected to have \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute pulmonary embolism (PE).\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET-wave inversion in right precordial leads,\u003C/strong\u003E along with sinus tachycardia, is this patient\u0027s most likely ECG abnormality. ST depression and T-wave inversion in the right precordial leads reflect the right ventricle strain resulting from an obstruction in the pulmonary artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EECG findings in \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute pulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E are not specific and sensitive but can help establish the provisional diagnosis. Common ECG changes noted in acute pulmonary embolism are shown in the table below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E S-T segment elevation in the lateral leads \u003C/strong\u003Eis most likely seen in \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral wall myocardial infarction. \u003C/strong\u003EThis patient\u0027s history of sudden onset dyspnea and left-sided pleuritic chest pain in the background of long immobilisation makes the diagnosis of pulmonary embolism more likely.\u003Cbr /\u003EThis patient\u0027s \u003Cstrong\u003Etroponin I\u003C/strong\u003E levels are only minimally raised, which can also be seen in the case of acute pulmonary embolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENew onset left bundle branch block \u003C/strong\u003Eis not seen in acute pulmonary embolism. This finding is common in the case of \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft ventricular infarction.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EST-segment elevation in all the precordial leads \u003C/strong\u003Eis very unlikely to be seen in cases of acute pulmonary embolism. Generalised ST-segment elevation in precordial leads is the common finding seen in \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute pericarditis.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged QT- interval \u003C/strong\u003Eis not seen in acute pulmonary embolism.\u003Cbr /\u003EThis ECG finding is sometimes seen in patients taking \u003Cstrong\u003Eselective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs)\u003C/strong\u003E like \u003Cstrong\u003Ecitalopram\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eescitalopram.\u003C/strong\u003E This patient is taking \u003Cstrong\u003Efluoxetine\u003C/strong\u003E for his panic disorder. Prolonged QT interval is not associated with fluoxetine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute pulmonary embolism is characterised by sudden-onset pleuritic chest pain and shortness of breath.","The common ECG changes in PE are sinus tachycardia, right bundle branch block, and right ventricular strain pattern (S-T segment depression and T-wave inversion) in right precordial leads.","Only 10% of the patients with PE may have classic ECG findings of S1Q3T3 (i.e., prominent S wave in lead I, prominent Q wave in lead III, and inverted T wave in lead III)."],"references":["Gruettner J, Viergutz T, Bolte M, Henzler T, Schoenberg SO, Sudarski S, Apfaltrer P, Walter T. Importance of risk factors for the evaluation of patients with a suspected pulmonary embolism. Exp Ther Med. 2015 Jun;9(6):2281-2284. doi: 10.3892/etm.2015.2395. Epub 2015 Mar 30. PMID: 26136974; PMCID: PMC4473335. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26136974/","Doherty S. Pulmonary embolism An update. Aust Fam Physician. 2017 Nov;46(11):816-820. PMID: 29101916. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29101916/","Vyas V, Sankari A, Goyal A. Acute Pulmonary Embolism. [Updated 2024 Dec 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560551/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67867"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2396"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20335"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20335"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f5xE2rUM0dzSQvEBvg009cnqUGbgN7.